  "prompt": "What is Intel XDK?",
  "response": "Intel XDK was a cross-platform integrated development environment (IDE) designed to help developers create, test, and debug mobile and web applications. It allowed developers to build apps using HTML5, JavaScript, and CSS, and then deploy them across multiple platforms, including iOS, Android, and Windows. Intel XDK provided tools for app development, including a code editor, a debugger, and a device emulator.\n\nKey features of Intel XDK included:\n\n1. **Cross-Platform Development**: Write once, deploy to multiple platforms.\n2. **Cordova/PhoneGap Support**: Built-in support for Apache Cordova (formerly PhoneGap), enabling access to native device features.\n3. **App Designer**: A drag-and-drop interface for designing app layouts.\n4. **Debugging Tools**: Debug directly on your devices or use the built-in emulator.\n5. **Build Services**: Cloud-based build services to compile and package your apps for various platforms.\n6. **Performance Analyzer**: Tools to analyze and optimize the performance of your apps.\n\nIntel XDK was discontinued in January 2019, and Intel recommended developers to transition to other tools such as Microsoft Visual Studio Code with Cordova plugins or other cross-platform development frameworks like Ionic or React Native.",
